  "prompt": "What software do Ghibli / Japanese studios use to create anime?",
  "response": "Japanese anime studios, including Studio Ghibli, use a variety of software and tools for animation production, though Studio Ghibli has been known for its traditional hand-drawn animation techniques. Here are some commonly used software and tools in the anime industry:\n\n1. **Toon Boom Harmony**: This is a popular 2D animation software that many studios use for creating animated series and films. It supports both traditional frame-by-frame animation as well as cut-out animation techniques.\n\n2. **Maya**: While primarily a 3D animation software, Maya is sometimes used for integrating 3D elements into anime productions, especially for scenes that require complex structures or camera movements.\n\n3. **Adobe After Effects**: This software is widely used for compositing, visual effects, and motion graphics in animations and is often employed in the post-production phase.\n\n4. **RETAS Studio**: This is a suite specifically designed for 2D animation that includes modules for drawing, animating, and compositing. It's particularly popular in Japan.\n\n5. **Clip Studio Paint**: This digital painting software is frequently used by artists for character design, storyboarding, and creating backgrounds before animation.\n\n6. **TVPaint Animation**: A robust 2D animation software that supports hand-drawn animation and is favored by many studios for creating traditional-style animations.\n\n7. **OpenToonz**: An open-source software that is derived from the Toonz software used by Studio Ghibli for their productions. It provides a variety of tools suited for traditional and digital animation.\n\n8. **Blender**: While primarily known as a 3D animation software, some anime studios have begun to use Blender for specific high-quality visual scenes or for combining 3D elements with traditional 2D animation.\n\nStudio Ghibli, in particular, has maintained a strong connection to traditional hand-drawn techniques, even incorporating some technology for digital painting and compositing in their later works. Each studio may have its own preferences based on their workflow and the specific demands of their projects.",
